The paper proposes a tool that uses Natural Language Processing (NLP) and semantic rules to generate UML class diagrams from text documents describing user requirements. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of GATE (General Architecture of Text), which is a popular tool for NLP, indicating that the paper may also belong to the Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) sub-category. The paper's focus on generating UML diagrams using semantic rules suggests that it may also be relevant to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Finally, the paper's use of semantic annotations and text repositories suggests that it may also be relevant to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category.
